# Usability

End-user-facing interfaces (CLI wallets, GUI wallet, wallet RPC) must
prioritize ease of use. Minimize technical barriers for non-developer users.

This rule applies to **end-user surfaces only**. Developer-facing tools
(`monerod`/`shekyld` operator CLI, debug RPCs, raw transaction inspectors)
appropriately expose block heights, hex hashes, and raw byte counts —
those are the right output for their audience.

## Rules

- Prefer sensible defaults over requiring configuration. A new user should
  be able to run a wallet with zero flags.
- Error messages must be human-readable. Include what went wrong, why, and
  what the user can do about it. Per `35-secure-memory.mdc`, error messages
  must never contain secret material.
- CLI commands follow consistent verb-noun patterns
  (e.g., `shekyl wallet create`, `shekyl wallet send`).
- Avoid exposing internal jargon (raw block heights, hex hashes, byte
  counts) in user-facing wallet output unless explicitly requested via a
  verbose/debug flag.
- Provide progress indicators for long-running operations (sync, key
  generation, large send construction).
- Document every public Rust wallet API with usage examples, not just type
  signatures.
- Rust wallet APIs use the builder pattern or sensible defaults rather than
  requiring all parameters upfront.
